#Text=Aulavik National Park
#Text=Aulavik
#Text=National
#Text=Park
#Text=is a national park on Banks
#Text=Island in the Northwest Territories of Canada .
#Text=Understand
#Text=The park covers 12,200 km ² , a bit larger than Jamaica .
#Text=It was established in 1992 .
#Text=It is known for its access to the Thomsen River , one of the most northerly navigable rivers in North America .
#Text=Park office , ☏ +1867 777-8800 , ✉ inuvik.info@pc.gc.ca .
#Text=History
#Text=Prior to the arrival of the Thule culture in southern Banks Island there were some Pre-Dorset culture people living in what is now the Aulavik National Park .
#Text=Due to the cooling climate brought on by the Little Ice Age , Banks Island was most likely deserted until the arrival of the Inuvialuit in the 17th century .
#Text=Aulavik National Park has two major bays , Castel Bay and Mercy Bay , and lies south of the McClure Strait .
#Text=Captain Robert McClure , spent two winters in Mercy Bay on HMS Investigator , while searching for the missing expedition of John Franklin between 1850 and 1853 .
#Text=McClure 's team abandoned their ship in Mercy Bay and hiked across the sea-ice of the strait to board another ship , HMS Resolute .
#Text=The Mercy Bay area was visited by the Copper Inuit of Victoria Island to salvage materials left by McClure 's party .
#Text=They also hunted the caribou and muskox in the area as evidenced by the large number of food caches .
#Text=In the 20th century the area was popular with Inuvialuit due to the large population of foxes .
#Text=Until the fur trade went into decline , fox trapping provided a source of income for people from as far away as the Mackenzie Delta and the North Slope of Alaska .
#Text=This influx of people led to the establishment of Sachs Harbour , the only community on the island .
#Text=Landscape
#Text=The park protects Arctic Lowlands at the northern end of the island .
#Text=In the southern regions of the park a sparsely vegetated upland plateau reaches a height of above sea level .
#Text=Flora and fauna
#Text=The park has the highest concentration of muskoxen on earth , with estimates of 68,000 to 80,000 animals on the island , approximately 20 % of which are thought to reside in the park .
#Text=It is also home to the endangered Peary caribou , and the more common barren-ground caribou .
#Text=Ptarmigan and ravens are considered the only year-round birds in the park , although 43 species make seasonal use of the area .
#Text=The park is completely treeless , and Arctic foxes , brown and northern collared lemmings , Arctic hares and wolves roam the rugged terrain .
#Text=Marine mammals along the north coast include polar bears , ringed seals , bearded seals , beluga whales and bowhead whales .
#Text=Birds of prey in the park include snowy owls , rough-legged hawks , gyrfalcons , and peregrine falcons , who feed on the lemmings .
#Text=Climate
#Text=Aulavik is considered a polar desert and often experiences high winds .
#Text=Precipitation for the park is approximately per year .
#Text=Get in
#Text=The park is accessible by chartered airplanes for only a brief period each summer .
#Text=The most practical way to visit the park is to charter a plane .
#Text=The park has four landing sites .
#Text=Aircraft charter services are available from Inuvik , on the Northwest Territories mainland , 750 km southwest of the southern park boundary .
#Text=Inuvik is the largest community in the region and is served by the Dempster Highway and by daily flights from southern Canada .
#Text=Fees and permits
#Text=Northern Park Backcountry Excursion/Camping Permit valid at Aulavik , Auyuittuq , Ivvavik , Nahanni , Quttinirpaaq , Sirmilik , Tuktut Nogait and Vuntut National Parks ( per person , 2018 ) :
#Text=Daily $ 24.50
#Text=Annual $ 147.20
#Text=Fishing permit :
#Text=Daily $ 9.80
#Text=Annual $ 34.30
#Text=See and do

#Text=Canoe on the 160 km of the gentle Thomsen River that runs the length of Aulavik National Park -- a multi-week journey through rich arctic tundra , full of wildlife like muskoxen , hundreds of species of wildflowers and ancient archaeological sites .
#Text=Hike through the low Arctic tundra .
#Text=There are no marked trails .
#Text=Buy , eat and drink
#Text=There are no facilities in the park .
#Text=You must bring everything with you .
#Text=Sleep
#Text=There are no designated campsites in the park .
#Text=You may camp anywhere you like , except at archaeological sites .
#Text=Please practice " no trace camping " .
#Text=All garbage must be packed out with you .
#Text=Consult with the Park Office in Inuvik for additional advice on low-impact camping techniques .
#Text=The winds can be very strong and prolonged in Aulavik National Park .
#Text=Bring a good quality tent , able to withstand fierce winds .
#Text=Campfires are not allowed in Aulavik .
#Text=Use a camp stove and bottled fuel for cooking .
#Text=Scheduled aircraft do not allow passengers to carry fuel .
#Text=Most types of camping fuel may be purchased in Inuvik , and some are available in Sachs Harbour .
#Text=Managing human waste : select a level site well away from any water sources .
#Text=Dig a small hole within the active layer of the soil .
#Text=If possible , choose an organic area and afterwards burn the toilet paper before carefully burying what remains .
#Text=If your group is large , it may be best to choose a communal location as opposed to many scattered sites .
